VALUES
(40, 4, 8, 58, 11, 24, 26, 'all the kingdoms of the world', 'Temptation of Earthly Riches', 'This connection highlights the choice between worldly glory and spiritual integrity. Both passages emphasize the allure of earthly kingdoms and treasures, contrasting them with the value of faith and suffering for a higher purpose.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 4, 8, 60, 1, 24, 24, 'the glory of them', 'Connection of Human Glory', 'This connection highlights the transient nature of human glory. In Matthew, the devil shows the glory of kingdoms, while 1 Peter contrasts this with the fleeting glory of man, emphasizing that all glory ultimately fades.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 4, 9, 47, 4, 4, 4, 'worship me', 'Connection of Worship and Blindness', 'This connection highlights the theme of worship and its consequences. In Matthew, the temptation to worship the devil is linked to gaining worldly power, while in 2 Corinthians, the ''god of this world'' blinds those who do not believe, preventing them from seeing the truth of the gospel.', 'theme', 0.349, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 4, 9, 27, 5, 18, 19, 'worship me', 'Authority and Worship Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority and power granted by God. In Matthew, the offer to worship reflects the control over kingdoms seen in Daniel, where Nebuchadnezzar''s authority is emphasized.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 4, 9, 43, 16, 11, 11, NULL, 'Judgment of the Prince', 'This connection highlights the authority of the ''prince of this world'' in both passages. In Matthew, the temptation to worship reflects the power of this figure, while John declares that this prince has been judged.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 4, 9, 66, 19, 10, 10, 'worship me', 'Worship and Authority Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of worship in both passages. In Matthew, the temptation to worship is presented in the context of authority, while in Revelation, the act of worship is redirected to God, emphasizing proper devotion.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 4, 9, 66, 22, 8, 9, 'worship me', 'Worship and Authority Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of worship and authority. In Matthew, the devil offers power in exchange for worship, while in Revelation, John is instructed not to worship the angel, emphasizing that worship is due only to God.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 4, 9, 19, 72, 11, 11, 'fall down and worship me', 'Worship and Service to Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of worship and submission to authority. In Matthew 4:9, the offer to worship is contrasted with Psalms 72:11, where all kings are depicted as falling down before a sovereign figure.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 4, 9, 46, 10, 20, 21, 'worship me', 'Worship and Sacrifice Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of worship and the consequences of idolatry. Both passages emphasize the idea of worshiping false entities, with Matthew referencing the temptation to worship the devil and 1 Corinthians warning against sacrificing to devils.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 4, 10, 5, 6, 13, 14, 'worship the Lord thy God', 'Worship and Service to God', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of worshiping and serving the Lord alone, rejecting other gods. This connection highlights the importance of fidelity to God as central to faith.', 'theme', 0.986, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 4, 10, 5, 10, 20, 20, 'worship the Lord thy God', 'Worship and Service to God', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of serving and worshiping the Lord God exclusively. Matthew 4:10 directly quotes the command to worship God, paralleling the directive in Deuteronomy 10:20 to serve Him.', 'theme', 0.6779999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 4, 10, 6, 24, 14, 14, NULL, 'Worship and Service to God', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of serving the Lord exclusively. Matthew 4:10 highlights worshiping God alone, while Joshua 24:14 calls for sincere service to Him, rejecting other gods.', 'theme', 0.538, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 4, 10, 42, 4, 8, 8, 'Thou shalt worship the Lord thy God', 'Connection of Jesus'' Response', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' rejection of Satan''s temptation by quoting the same scripture about worshiping God. This connection highlights the consistency in Jesus'' message across the Gospels.', 'quotation', 0.475, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 4, 10, 9, 7, 3, 3, NULL, 'Worship and Service to God', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of serving God exclusively. Matthew 4:10 quotes the command to worship the Lord, while 1 Samuel 7:3 calls for Israel to serve Him only, highlighting a consistent theme of devotion.', 'theme', 0.46799999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 4, 10, 59, 4, 7, 7, 'worship the Lord thy God', 'Worship and Resistance to Evil', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of submitting to God and resisting evil. In Matthew, Jesus commands worship of God alone, while James instructs believers to submit to God and resist the devil.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 4, 10, 60, 5, 9, 9, 'Get thee hence, Satan', 'Resisting Satan''s Influence', 'This connection highlights the theme of resisting Satan. In Matthew, Jesus commands Satan to leave, emphasizing worship of God alone, while 1 Peter encourages believers to resist Satan steadfastly in faith, acknowledging shared struggles.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 4, 11, 40, 26, 53, 53, 'angels came and ministered unto him', 'Angels'' Role in Ministry', 'This connection highlights the presence of angels in both passages. In Matthew 4:11, angels minister to Jesus after his temptation, while in Matthew 26:53, Jesus refers to the possibility of calling upon angels for assistance.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 4, 11, 42, 22, 43, 43, 'angels came and ministered unto him', 'Angelic Ministry in Distress', 'Both passages emphasize the role of angels in providing strength during moments of temptation and distress. In Matthew, angels minister to Jesus after his temptation, while in Luke, an angel strengthens him in Gethsemane.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 4, 11, 58, 1, 14, 14, 'ministered unto him', 'Angelic Ministry in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the role of angels as ministering spirits. Both passages emphasize the function of angels in providing support and ministry to those in need, particularly to Jesus and the heirs of salvation.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 4, 11, 42, 4, 13, 13, 'the devil leaveth him', 'Temptation and Departure of the Devil', 'Both passages emphasize the departure of the devil after temptation. Matthew notes that the devil leaves, while Luke states he departs for a season, highlighting a similar narrative moment.', 'parallel', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 4, 11, 66, 5, 11, 12, 'angels came and ministered unto him', 'Angelic Ministry and Worship', 'This connection highlights the role of angels in both passages. In Matthew, angels minister to Jesus after His temptation, while in Revelation, angels proclaim the worthiness of the Lamb, emphasizing their ongoing service and worship.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 4, 11, 40, 4, 6, 6, 'angels came and ministered unto him', 'Angels and Divine Protection', 'Both passages emphasize the role of angels in providing protection. In Matthew 4:6, the devil quotes scripture about angels bearing one up, while Matthew 4:11 describes angels ministering to Jesus after his temptation.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 4, 11, 41, 1, 13, 13, 'angels came and ministered unto him', 'Angels Ministering After Temptation', 'Both passages emphasize the role of angels ministering to Jesus after his temptation in the wilderness. This connection highlights the divine support provided to Jesus during a time of trial.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 4, 12, 41, 1, 14, 14, 'John was cast into prison', 'Jesus'' Ministry Begins After John''s Imprisonment', 'Both passages emphasize the timing of Jesus'' ministry following John''s imprisonment. This connection highlights the transition in focus from John the Baptist to Jesus in Galilee.', 'parallel', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 4, 12, 42, 3, 20, 20, NULL, 'Connection of John''s Imprisonment', 'Both passages emphasize John''s imprisonment, which serves as a pivotal moment in Jesus'' ministry. Matthew notes Jesus'' departure into Galilee following John''s imprisonment, while Luke highlights the act of John being shut up in prison.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 4, 12, 40, 14, 3, 3, 'John was cast into prison', 'Connection of John''s Imprisonment', 'This connection highlights the event of John''s imprisonment, which is mentioned in both passages. Matthew 4:12 notes Jesus'' departure after hearing about John''s imprisonment, while Matthew 14:3 provides the reason for John''s imprisonment.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 4, 12, 42, 4, 14, 14, 'departed into Galilee', 'Jesus'' Ministry in Galilee', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' movement into Galilee following John''s imprisonment. Both passages emphasize the significance of Galilee as the starting point for Jesus'' ministry.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 4, 12, 41, 6, 17, 17, 'John was cast into prison', 'John''s Imprisonment and Jesus'' Ministry', 'This connection highlights the event of John''s imprisonment, which is mentioned in both passages. Matthew notes Jesus'' departure into Galilee after hearing of John''s imprisonment, while Mark details the circumstances of John''s imprisonment by Herod.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 4, 12, 43, 3, 24, 24, 'John was cast into prison', 'John''s Imprisonment Timeline', 'This connection highlights the timeline of John the Baptist''s imprisonment. Matthew 4:12 indicates that Jesus began his ministry after John''s imprisonment, while John 3:24 states that John was not yet imprisoned, suggesting a chronological sequence.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 4, 12, 43, 4, 43, 43, 'he departed into Galilee', 'Jesus'' Movement to Galilee', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' departure into Galilee, indicating a significant geographical movement in his ministry. This connection highlights the continuity of Jesus'' actions following John''s imprisonment.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
